result.execSummary:
The defendant Javier S Murillo was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Substantial Battery-Intend Bodily Harm [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Incident], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(2).
  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

MOTION TO AMEND AND CLARIFY THE JUDGMENT OF CONVICTION received.
Original Transcript (13 pages) commencing SENTENCING HEARING - EXCERPT  08/22/2014. received and filed.
Count one.
Count two.

Defendant Javier S Murillo in court with attorney Craig S. Powell.  Nicolas J. Heitman appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by counsel, the defendant and the court.  AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court imposed the following sentence:
Defendant's TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE shall be 3 YEARS consecutive to any other sentence.  Defendant's TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin Prison System shall be for 1 YEAR, 6 MONTHS with credit for 0 days time served.  Defendant shall serve 1 YEAR, 6 MONTHS on EXTENDED SUPERVISION.  The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  The Court advised the defendant of his determinate sentence pursuant to statute and in accordance with Form CR-234.  Copy provided to defendant.  The Court STAYED THE SENTENCE and placed the defendant on probation to the State Department of Corrections for a period of 3 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE TO COUNT 2.
CONDITIONS OF PROBATION & EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- As a condition of probation, the Court ordered the defendant to serve 5 MONTHS in the House of Correction, STRAIGHT TIME.  Court further ordered defendant to serve 100 days in the House of Correction.  This time is stayed pending review hearing. 
- Attend the following programs and/or assessments:  Mental Health Evaluation and Take all Prescribed Medication.
- Attend treatment and counseling programs as determined by agent.
- Maintain absolute sobriety.
- No contact with Nicole N. and Anthony L. without approval of the court or agent.
- Third-party contact for purpose of time with children as approved by agent.
- Obtain/maintain employment.
- Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor.
- Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored. 
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample and pay DNA analysis surcharge under 973.046(1g).
- Pay supervision fees as determined by the Wisconsin Department of Corrections.
- Pay all costs, fees and assessments, any cash bail to apply.  Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment.
- Make all child support payments.
- Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.  Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief received and filed.  Ineligible Voting Notice & Acknowledgement received and filed; copy to defendant.
Court ordered a probation review hearing to be held within 100 days of defendant's release from custody.
AS TO COUNT 2:  The Court ordered the Defendant to serve 8 MONTHS in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence with credit for 1 day time served, STRAIGHT TIME, FORTHWITH.  Court ordered a DNA surcharge and all costs, fees, assessments and surcharges to be paid during period of probation in Count 1.

AS TO COUNTS 1 & 2
  Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record. Court advised defendant of penalties for violation of NO CONTACT ORDER. Court advised that under 48 USC Section 922(g)(9) the defendant is prohibited from possession of a firearm and/or ammunition after conviction of a misdemeanor crime of domestic violence.Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession or, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored. Case adjourned to branch 23 for Sentencing.
